SIMPLE: speak
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Speak
<hw>Speak</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos>
<conjf>Spoke</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> (<conjf>Spake</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>
<mark>Archaic</mark>); <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Spoken</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr> (<conjf>Spoke</conjf>, <mark>Obs. <plain>or</plain>
Colloq.</mark>); <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Speaking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>speken</ets>, AS.
<ets>specan</ets>, <ets>sprecan</ets>; akin to OF.ries.
<ets>spreka</ets>, D. <ets>spreken</ets>, OS. <ets>spreken</ets>, G.
<ets>sprechen</ets>, OHG. <ets>sprehhan</ets>, and perhaps to Skr.
<ets>sph⟦umac⟧rj</ets> to crackle, to thunder. Cf. <er>Spark</er> of
fire, <er>Speech</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To utter words or
articulate sounds, as human beings; to express thoughts by words;
<as>as, the organs may be so obstructed that a man may not be able to
<ex>speak</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Till at the last <qex>spake</qex> in this manner.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Speak</qex>, Lord; for thy servant heareth.</q> <rj><qau>1
Sam. iii. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To express opinions; to say; to talk; to
converse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That fluid substance in a few minutes begins to set, as the
tradesmen <qex>speak</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Boyle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An honest man, is able to <qex>speak</qex> for himself, when a
knave is not.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>During the century and a half which followed the Conquest, there
is, to <qex>speak</qex> strictly, no English history.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To utter a speech, discourse, or harangue; to adress
a public assembly formally.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Many of the nobility made themselves popular by
<qex>speaking</qex> in Parliament against those things which were most
grateful to his majesty.</q> <rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To discourse; to make mention; to tell.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lycan <qex>speaks</qex> of a part of Caesar's army that came to
him from the Leman Lake.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To give sound; to sound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Make all our trumpets <qex>speak</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To convey sentiments, ideas, or intelligence as if
by utterance; <as>as, features that <ex>speak</ex> of
self-will</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thine eye begins to <qex>speak</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To speak of</b></col>, <cd>to take account of, to make
mention of.</cd> <au>Robynson (More's Utopia).</au> -- <col><b>To speak
out</b></col>, <cd>to speak loudly and distinctly; also, to speak
unreservedly.</cd> -- <col><b>To speak well for</b></col>, <cd>to
commend; to be favorable to.</cd> -- <col><b>To speak with</b></col>,
<cd>to converse with.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Would you <xex>speak with</xex>
me?⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To say; tell; talk; converse; discourse;
articulate; pronounce; utter.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Speak</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Speak
<hw>Speak</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To utter
with the mouth; to pronounce; to utter articulately, as human
beings.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They sat down with him upn ground seven days and seven nights, and
none <qex>spake</qex> a word unto him.</q> <rj><qau>Job. ii.
13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To utter in a word or words; to say; to tell; to
declare orally; <as>as, to <ex>speak</ex> the truth; to <ex>speak</ex>
sense</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To declare; to proclaim; to publish; to make known;
to exhibit; to express in any way.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is my father;s muste⟦br⟧
To <qex>speak</qex> your deeds.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Speaking</qex> a still good morrow with her eyes.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And for the heaven's wide circuit, let it <qex>speak</qex>⟦br⟧
The maker's high magnificence.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Report <qex>speaks</qex> you a bonny monk.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To talk or converse in; to utter or pronounce, as in
conversation; <as>as, to <ex>speak</ex> Latin</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And French she <qex>spake</qex> full fair and fetisely.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To address; to accost; to speak to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[He will] thee in hope; he will <qex>speak</qex> thee fair.</q>
<rj><qau>Ecclus. xiii. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>each village senior paused to scan⟦br⟧
And <qex>speak</qex> the lovely caravan.</q>
<rj><qau>Emerson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To speak a ship</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to hail
and speak to her captain or commander.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Speakable</ent>⟦br⟧
